Description:
Northamptonshire County Council wishes to invite tenders for a civil parking enforcement service. The successful provider will be committed and able to provide a high quality parking enforcement service, which encompasses its strategy, policy and one which can adapt to the changing needs of its stakeholders whilst ensuring that the Service is delivered in a cost effective manner. The successful provider will provide a 'seamless' Service in the management of the County's on and off-street parking regulation.
The enforcement operation covered by this contract includes:
- issue of notices for all on and off street Permitted parking place contraventions within the CEA of Northamptonshire ;
- All operating as defined by The Road Traffic Regulation Act 1984, and Traffic Management Act 2004, as amended;
- implementation of suspensions;
- management of elements of the parking infrastructure to include PDMs maintenance (routine first-line, reactive and planned); and
- management and provision of the IT infrastructure required by the Contractors' Staff to enable the Services to be delivered using equipment and information provided from time to time by the Council which includes the existing stock of HHCTs, printers, radios, and the allowed access to information from the Council's ICES 3Sixty(Back Office) notice processing system and PowerCube and other modules.
This Contract is for 6 years with an option to extend for up to 6 years, making 12 years in total.

The Royal Borough of Windsor & Maidenhead requires the implementation of a coordinated operation based
around the provision, management and enforcement of on and off-street parking spaces and the processing of
Penalty Charge Notices (27,698 issued in 2016 calendar year) and Fixed Penalty Notices (157 issued in the
2015/16 calendar year), supported by a fully hosted web enabled browser based IT system including online
payment functionality.

The control of parking in RBWM is based upon the policy objectives of the Authority, which include:

• to restrain the use of vehicles, particularly in the busiest locations, at the busiest times, without undermining
the economic life of the towns;
• to provide adequate long and short-stay parking to support shops, commercial and leisure activities;
• to protect the needs of residents, businesses and visitors, including through the use of permit parking
schemes;
• to use town centre parking charging strategies to discourage growth in the use of the car and encourage the
use of public transport and other modes of travel, without undermining the economic life of the urban areas;
• to protect the environment;
• to improve the conditions for movement of pedestrians and cyclists;
• to provide adequate off street commuter parking to reduce on street parking around the transport network;
• to control off-street parking.
